    <summary>In this email exchange, Andreas Schildbach and an unknown recipient discuss the use of iso-dep for a payment system via cell phone. However, there are concerns about the connection breaking as soon as the phone is picked up. They suggest that if the phone cannot immediately authorize, then HTTPS or Bluetooth could be used instead. The memo field in the payment system presents challenges for risk analysis. The email also discusses the current use of NFC for Bitcoin transactions with Andreas' Wallet being the only one supporting it. The writer suggests adding Bitcoin support to London's contactless payment system, Oyster, without hardware replacements. They propose using transaction fees to define a cap on confirmationless payments. Alex Kotenko discusses the potential value of Bitcoin v0.9 and its transaction fees. Jan Vornberger and Alex Kotenko discuss the use of NFC for Bitcoin transactions and suggest switching to BIP70 as soon as possible. Finally, the context includes discussions about the possibility of generating a PDF receipt and sending it via NFC to avoid an additional tap during payment, and using contactless cards for payment instead of enrolling specifically for Oyster card in London.In various email conversations and discussions, several individuals discuss the implementation of Bitcoin technology in payment systems. The focus is on improving usability and security to match the seamless experience provided by contactless payments made through NFC technology. Suggestions for improvement include the use of HD wallets, the development of a decentralized reputation network based on social data exchange, and the optimization of bootup processes and communication latency. Other topics discussed include the use of Bluetooth and host card emulation (HCE) in wallets, the viability of using PDF-based paperless processes for proof of payment, and the challenges presented by bulky X.509 certificates in payment request messages. The importance of a consistent and intuitive user experience is emphasized throughout the conversations.In email exchanges and conversations from 2014 among members of the Bitcoin-development mailing list, several ideas were discussed regarding the implementation of a feedback system for Bitcoin payments, the limitations of NFC payments on smartphones, the need for a third party to keep merchants honest, and the usage of Bluetooth and NFC technology in wallets and POS systems. The proposed feedback system would allow users to provide feedback on a payment using an ECDSA signature from one of the addresses involved in the payment, but concerns were raised about what constitutes a "Bitcoin user" and the possibility of paying oneself to accrue positive reputation. The limitations of NFC payments on smartphones were discussed, and it was noted that future OSes may allow payment apps on the lock screen. The lack of chargebacks in Bitcoin transactions presents a clear risk to the customer, so a proposal was made for a third party to keep merchants honest, opening up markets for transaction insurance companies. Several ideas were suggested for a decentralized reputation network, including the use of Stealth addresses or HD wallet roots as identities for gaining reputation. Finally, the conversation included discussions on HCE features and the experience of contactless payments in different countries.In the given context, there are discussions about the potential value of Bitcoin v0.9 and its transaction fees. The author believes that Bitcoin can solve the problems faced by contactless NFC payments due to the small payment range and minimum payment sizes required by merchants. The use of BIP70 protocol is also discussed, with Alex Kotenko expressing the need for more wallets to support it. Bitcoin Wallet has been supporting the customer side of the protocol since 2011, and the merchant side has recently removed the Labs enabling. There is also a proposal for using a Stealth address or HD wallet root as an identity for gaining reputation. The implementation of Bluetooth and NFC technology in wallets and point-of-sale (POS) systems is also discussed, with Andreas Schildbach providing updates on Android's host card emulation (HCE) feature. Mike Hearn suggests optimising the bootup process of the Android wallet app to improve the user experience.Bitcoin wallet users can interoperate with BIP70, although the customer side of the protocol is only available as a "Labs feature" that will be turned off for most users. The merchant side of the protocol used to require Labs enabling, but this has been done away with in recent weeks. There have been discussions about generating a PDF receipt and sending it via NFC to avoid an additional tap during payment. Contactless cards were also discussed, with some suggesting that Oyster and similar city cards may eventually be phased out as contactless credit cards become more prevalent. There have been proposals for implementing a feedback system for Bitcoin payments, which would allow users to provide feedback on a payment using an ECDSA signature from one of the addresses involved in the payment, signing an identifier of the payment and a feedback score. However, questions were raised about what constitutes a "Bitcoin user" and what would stop someone from paying themselves to accrue positive reputation. The importance of a consistent and intuitive user experience was emphasized, with suggestions for optimizing the bootup process of the Android wallet app and using a</summary>
